useful, because they

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:34.650
relate to the things I'm going
to talk about, one of which

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:37.410
is "Evolution is
apparently intent

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.930
that man fulfil a much
greater destiny than that

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:43.890
of being a simple muscle
and reflex machine."

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:45.734
And I think that
presentations that we've

00:04:45.734 --> 00:04:47.400
heard this morning
and the conversations

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:49.290
that you must have
as an organization

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:51.990
relate to this
tension where we know

00:04:51.990 --> 00:04:56.100
that the computer is there to
help us become something more.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:58.060
It's just that so
much of our society

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.860
is actually built on the
idea of us being less

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:05.320
and being a reflex
muscle, machine.

00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:10.400
The other one is--

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:12.220
and they're from
the same person,

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:13.535
weirdly, in the same book.

00:05:13.535 --> 00:05:14.510
So it's quite handy.

00:05:14.510 --> 00:05:17.150
And I have that book here--

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:20.630
is the "Behavior of
whole systems unpredicted

00:05:20.630 --> 00:05:22.910
by the separately
observed behaviors of any

00:05:22.910 --> 00:05:25.760
of the system's separate
parts or any subassembly

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:27.770
of the system's parts."

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:31.790
This is the definition
of Buckminster Fuller

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:37.190
for the word synergy, which we
don't use on purpose at all.

00:05:37.190 --> 00:05:39.430
We kind of use in
quotation marks.

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:40.880
It's like the word
that everybody

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:43.280
hates using but
sometimes accidentally

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:46.670
uses to mean something
completely different.

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:48.350
And I find that
fascinating, because I

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:51.080
think that a lot of
the conversations that

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:55.640
are happening in the world,
that Sarah's work encapsulates,

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:58.640
some of the people who are here
from doteveryone encapsulates,

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:00.700
and some of my work
these days encapsulates

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:04.460
is this misunderstanding
of the parts

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:08.630
and misunderstanding of
the influence on the whole.

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:11.780
So maybe we should take
synergy and revisit it

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:13.695
with Buckminster Fuller's
sort of approach.

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:20.060
And I think, these
days, I kind of

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:22.250
feel like we're prepared
for the apocalypse

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:24.000
that we sort of planned for.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.570
We have this imagery,
for the last 100 years--

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:28.470
and I'm writing a book
about smart homes.

00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:33.920
So let me tell you I'm basking
in images of the future that

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:38.480
are very much about
things being connected,

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:42.830
this kind of hyperconnectivity
and, ultimately, a future

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:46.010
that is mathematically
coherent somehow.

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:48.450
There's always a circle.

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:50.755
There's always a
circle around things.

00:06:50.755 --> 00:06:53.190
There's always circles
within circles.

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:54.960
There's lines of things.

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:57.510
Everything kind
of mathematically

00:06:57.510 --> 00:06:59.940
somehow makes sense.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:02.900
And visually, we feel like,
yeah, yeah, this is totally it.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:07.057
This is totally
the future we want.

00:07:07.057 --> 00:07:08.890
And I find that that's,
of course, a problem

00:07:08.890 --> 00:07:10.450
because I don't
think that it allows

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:15.220
us to account for the times
when it's not like that, which

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:17.620
is almost always.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:20.920
But we feel like we want
this future somehow,

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.535
because, you know, a
circle is a great shape.

00:07:23.535 --> 00:07:27.750
It's a great shape
to believe in.

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:29.430
Triangles are also great shapes.

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:31.630
You use them a lot.

00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:35.370
I don't have a triangle
in this presentation.

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:38.010
But I find it more interesting
to think about futures

00:07:38.010 --> 00:07:39.750
that are completely incoherent.

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:42.820
And this is only a
very recent position.

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:46.090
This is not the kind of stuff
that I have done my whole life.

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:51.120
This is just a compound
of events and projects

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:54.210
that I have spent more
and more of my time

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:55.890
on that I'd like
to share with you.

00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:02.840
Predominantly, something
called the Open IoT Mark.

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:06.580
I'll talk about what it is,
but it is a baby project.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.610
It's sort of at its infancy.

00:08:08.610 --> 00:08:11.360
It's less than a year old.

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.600
And it is an attempt
by a community

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:16.000
of people that are
less than 100 to look

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:21.670
at what it might mean to create
a certification mark for IoT.

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:26.190
So think of Fair Trade and
the Fair Trade sticker.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:30.820
77% of British people know what
a Fair Trade sticker means.

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:34.650
It's a very clear, very
well-publicized sticker.

00:08:34.650 --> 00:08:36.400
Think of what that
might mean in the world

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:38.650
of connected products.

00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:40.630
What does trust
mean, ethics mean?

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.360
How do we do something
that is a Fair Trade

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:47.024
sticker for the world
of connected products?

00:08:47.024 --> 00:08:48.190
That's what we're exploring.

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:50.398
That's what I'm spending
more and more of my time on.

00:08:53.740 --> 00:08:56.900
And in the things that we're
exploring-- and this is a very,

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:59.690
again, small group of
people, mostly technologists,

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:02.690
would really appreciate
anyone in this room,

00:09:02.690 --> 00:09:05.180
and in the extended
Google family

00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:07.760
to have a look at what we're
doing-- but we're exploring

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:09.730
ideas of trusts and risk.

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:15.257
This is the more recent--

00:09:15.257 --> 00:09:17.840
I suppose it's not technically
the more recent of my examples,

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:20.450
but it's the more recent
in a tangible way, which

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:22.925
is the VW emissions scandal.

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:28.650
A corporation, which
I shall not name,

00:09:28.650 --> 00:09:32.690
which is German,
and a foundation,

00:09:32.690 --> 00:09:39.930
provided the censors to VW to
actually measure the emissions.

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:42.690
And in the world of
engineering, doing that,

00:09:42.690 --> 00:09:45.570
you have to do it in
a very particular way.

00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:48.660
And so someone, somewhere
sent an email to VW

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:53.820
to say, yeah, by the
way, just keep in mind

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.370
that this could be abused.

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:57.720
We're selling you this sensor.

00:09:57.720 --> 00:09:59.370
It's going to go
in all your cars.

00:09:59.370 --> 00:10:04.740
And you do what you want to
do with it, but just be aware.

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:07.440
And by doing that, have
absolved themselves

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:09.570
of any responsibility publicly.

00:10:09.570 --> 00:10:11.340
They are not the
corporation which

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:14.520
is the one that
makes the headlines.

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:16.350
Because from an
engineering perspective,

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.270
they did the right thing.

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:19.950
And they did the
commendable thing,

00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:22.860
and the protectable thing
in the eyes of the law

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:27.070
by sending that one email
from that one engineer, which

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:29.700
is really interesting.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:31.950
Because that's what
trust means and risks

00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:36.630
means within that area.

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:39.360
Who knows where this is?

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:41.990
Brownie points if you do.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:42.840
You can yell it out.

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:52.800
Christchurch in New Zealand,
some years ago, obviously.

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:55.860
And I always think of trust
and risk in an engineering

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:58.590
space as this
space where we also

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:03.960
are quite happy to bumble along
with crappy decision making

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:08.550
and crappy structures of
living until something happens

00:11:08.550 --> 00:11:12.060
that makes us go, mm, I
guess that we'll build things

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:17.640
in an earthquake safe manner
now, because the cost of change

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:18.900
is high.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:21.000
The cost of taking
every single building

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.700
in New Zealand in both
islands and saying we're

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:26.370
going to tear everything
down and we're

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:30.240
going to rebuild it all to
code so that it's earthquake

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:33.120
safe is not feasible.

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:36.330
So we tend to wait till
bad things happen in order

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:39.166
to operate any change.

00:11:39.166 --> 00:11:40.540
And this is because
we're people.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:41.260
We're human.

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:45.880
We assign a particular cost
to immediate decision making

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:50.200
and we forget about the cost
of later decision making.

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:53.290
We're very myopic that way.

00:11:56.230 --> 00:11:57.710
This is slightly more recent.

00:11:57.710 --> 00:12:01.390
Brownie points for who
knows where this is.

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:02.240
Yes.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:04.690
So, Florida.

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:07.570
Equally, here, the same
kind of conversation

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:09.520
around risk and trust.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:11.560
Which is the engineer
called two days

00:12:11.560 --> 00:12:16.389
before to say, hey, by the
way, we've seen some cracks.

00:12:16.389 --> 00:12:17.680
You might want to look at this.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:19.420
This might need to be patched.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:21.850
And now this engineer is--

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:25.270
his entire career is being
sort of dragged in the dirt

00:12:25.270 --> 00:12:28.430
because it turns out he was
involved in other projects.

00:12:28.430 --> 00:12:31.450
And oh, my god, what does this
mean for the other projects?

00:12:31.450 --> 00:12:33.190
As if that one
engineer was the one

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:36.400
responsible for an
entire project like this.

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:40.180
That no one else in the delivery
process, the people selling

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:43.906
the concrete, the people
okaying the launch,

00:12:43.906 --> 00:12:45.280
whatever it might
be, no one else

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:47.980
has any responsibility
but this one person.

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.002
So we think about that in
terms of big structures.

00:12:54.002 --> 00:12:55.960
We're kind of happy
thinking about those things

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:58.660
in terms of the structures
that surround us.

00:12:58.660 --> 00:13:00.980
But we're sort of less
comfortable with it,

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:03.550
or it's newer to think
about it, in the things that

00:13:03.550 --> 00:13:06.730
start to disappear around
us, the small devices,

00:13:06.730 --> 00:13:09.550
the small consumer
facing devices.

00:13:09.550 --> 00:13:11.920
We don't yet have a
really good structure

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:14.710
for what we should
expect, what risks looks

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:17.320
like, what trust looks like.

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:25.670
Or something as mundane and
as problematic as lifecycle.

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:29.330
We live in a world where
things will not last very long.

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:36.520
I am dragging my MacBook Pro
until it really literally dies

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:38.170
on me, even though I'm--

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:40.630
now, the nice people
next to me were probably

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:43.330
thinking who is this
person, because I'm

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:47.170
dragging an external keyboard,
because the keyboard died.

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:49.470
And I'm like I am
not giving up on you,

00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:52.510
if you don't give up on me.

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:55.990
Because I refused to
give said corporation

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.360
that starts with an A
a large amount of money

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:01.240
yet again every other year.

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:03.700
And this one, this
baby, is like--

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:05.210
I bought it in 2013.

00:14:05.210 --> 00:14:08.950
So I feel like I think we can
do another six months together,

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:10.760
I swear.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:12.270
But lifecycle is a problem.

00:14:12.270 --> 00:14:14.300
It's a problem in
everyday devices.

