whether that's standards boxes.

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:55.720
So I'm not going to be supplied
with the quality of plastic

00:26:55.720 --> 00:26:59.440
that might include some lead
if I make my toy out of it.

00:26:59.440 --> 00:27:03.700
There is trust and
legal frameworks

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:05.920
built into every supply chain.

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:08.290
We don't quite have
that connection

00:27:08.290 --> 00:27:11.330
between this hardware
and software space.

00:27:11.330 --> 00:27:14.140
And so a lot of the
projects that I showed--

00:27:14.140 --> 00:27:16.600
the 45 different projects
that are around the world--

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:20.920
a lot of them now are
concentrating on security,

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:23.920
because they feel like
that's an easier box

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:28.390
to tick than to look more
transversely at ownership,

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:30.640
permissions,
openness, et cetera.

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:34.060
Because it is about
that complex connection

00:27:34.060 --> 00:27:38.500
and back to that quote from
Buckminster Fuller, which

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:43.090
is the movement of each element
has unintended consequences

00:27:43.090 --> 00:27:44.660
at a larger scale.

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:47.140
So that's kind of
why we're choosing

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:50.200
to pick minimum viable
everything on lots

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:53.710
of different levels,
because I don't think

00:27:53.710 --> 00:27:58.420
it's future proof to
think in this siloed way

00:27:58.420 --> 00:28:02.120
that, well, you know, my
responsibility lies here.

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:03.985
No, you're still making
a car that pollutes.

